<paragraph id="8BA136D1FFAA765AFF08D1584B2EF00F" blockId="119.[163,282,1280,1301]" box="[163,282,1280,1301]" pageId="119" pageNumber="536">
<emphasis id="B96AEAC3FFAA765AFF08D1584B2EF00F" box="[163,282,1280,1301]" italics="true" pageId="119" pageNumber="536">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA136D1FFAA765AFF08D16649E6F42D" blockId="119.[163,779,1342,1395]" lastBlockId="119.[827,1443,197,311]" pageId="119" pageNumber="536">
<emphasis id="B96AEAC3FFAA765AFF08D1664ADBF049" box="[163,239,1342,1363]" italics="true" pageId="119" pageNumber="536">Males:</emphasis>
This species can be identified by the lack of prosomal modification, the short and wide palpal tibia, and its long, broad, retrolaterally curved, distally rounded and incurved prolateral apophysis, and the embolic division with a direct continuation of the radix and embolus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA136D1FFAA765AFC90D5384F1BF4A9" blockId="119.[827,1443,352,435]" pageId="119" pageNumber="536">
<emphasis id="B96AEAC3FFAA765AFC90D53849AFF46F" box="[827,923,352,373]" italics="true" pageId="119" pageNumber="536">Females:</emphasis>
Can be identified by the epigyne with a large, convex ventral plate and a deeply and widely emarginated dorsal plate (fig. 
<quantity id="4CE69B34FFAA765AFC45D5C54E11F4A9" box="[1006,1061,413,435]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.54" pageId="119" pageNumber="536" unit="in" value="10.0">10 in</quantity>
<bibRefCitation id="EF8F4B20FFAA765AFB80D5C54F14F4A9" author="Crosby CR &amp; Bishop SC" box="[1067,1312,413,435]" pageId="119" pageNumber="536" pagination="52 - 64" refId="ref90108" refString="Crosby CR, Bishop SC. 1936. Studies in American spiders: Miscellaneous genera of Erigoneae. Festschrift Embrik Strand 2: 52 - 64." type="journal article" year="1936">Crosby &amp; Bishop, 1936</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA136D1FFAA765AFC90D58449B4F63E" blockId="119.[827,1443,476,804]" pageId="119" pageNumber="536">
<emphasis id="B96AEAC3FFAA765AFC90D5844984F4EB" box="[827,944,476,497]" italics="true" pageId="119" pageNumber="536">Remarks:</emphasis>
After examining the 
<typeStatus id="54A58873FFAA765AFB7ED5844F3EF4EB" box="[1237,1290,476,497]" pageId="119" pageNumber="536">type</typeStatus>
material of 
<taxonomicName id="4C1E4D52FFAA765AFC90D5A24E77F715" authorityName="Ivie &amp; Barrows" authorityYear="1935" box="[827,1091,506,527]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Oedothorax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="119" pageNumber="536" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="seminolus">
<emphasis id="B96AEAC3FFAA765AFC90D5A24E77F715" box="[827,1091,506,527]" italics="true" pageId="119" pageNumber="536">Oedothorax seminolus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="13252A54FFAA765AFBFFD5A24E91F70A" box="[1108,1189,506,528]" captionStart="Figure 72" captionStartId="119.[164,243,1848,1870]" captionTargetBox="[166,1447,1485,1806]" captionTargetId="figure-559@119.[163,1450,1482,1809]" captionTargetPageId="119" captionText="Figure 72. Soulgas corticarius (Emerton, 1909). A, B, male left palp. A, retrolateral view. B, prolateral view. Scale bar 0.1 mm." pageId="119" pageNumber="536">Fig. 72</figureCitation>
) and comparing it to the descriptions of 
<taxonomicName id="4C1E4D52FFAA765AFB88D6414F38F735" box="[1059,1292,537,559]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" genus="Solugas" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="119" pageNumber="536" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="corticarius">
<emphasis id="B96AEAC3FFAA765AFB88D6414F38F735" box="[1059,1292,537,559]" italics="true" pageId="119" pageNumber="536">Solugas corticarius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation id="EF8F4B20FFAA765AFA91D64249B1F754" author="Emerton JH" pageId="119" pageNumber="536" pagination="171 - 236" refId="ref90670" refString="Emerton JH. 1909. Supplement to the New England spiders. Transactions of the Connecticut Academy of Arts and Sciences 14: 171 - 236." type="journal article" year="1909">Emerton (1909)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="EF8F4B20FFAA765AFC68D6604ED4F754" author="Crosby CR &amp; Bishop SC" box="[963,1248,568,590]" pageId="119" pageNumber="536" pagination="52 - 64" refId="ref90108" refString="Crosby CR, Bishop SC. 1936. Studies in American spiders: Miscellaneous genera of Erigoneae. Festschrift Embrik Strand 2: 52 - 64." type="journal article" year="1936">Crosby &amp; Bishop (1936)</bibRefCitation>
, we support the decision of 
<bibRefCitation id="EF8F4B20FFAA765AFC69D60E4E98F777" author="Buckle D &amp; Carroll D &amp; Crawford R &amp; Roth V" box="[962,1196,598,621]" pageId="119" pageNumber="536" pagination="89 - 191" refId="ref89563" refString="Buckle D, Carroll D, Crawford R, Roth V. 2001. Linyphiidae and Pimoidae of America north of Mexico: checklist, synonymy, and literature. Fabreries, Supplement 10: 89 - 191." type="journal article" year="2001">
Buckle 
<emphasis id="B96AEAC3FFAA765AFBB6D60F4E6DF771" box="[1053,1113,598,620]" italics="true" pageId="119" pageNumber="536">et al.</emphasis>
(2001)
</bibRefCitation>
that the former is a junior synonym of the latter. Palpal features, such as the lack of membranous connection between radix and embolus, and the shape and position of the embolic membrane, indicate that this species does not belong to 
<taxonomicName id="4C1E4D52FFAA765AFC71D6A84E54F61F" authorityName="Triceps Tanasevitch" authorityYear="2020" box="[986,1120,752,773]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Oedothorax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="119" pageNumber="536" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B96AEAC3FFAA765AFC71D6A84E54F61F" box="[986,1120,752,773]" italics="true" pageId="119" pageNumber="536">Oedothorax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as delimited in the present study.
</paragraph>
